457. Nil non permittit] The women come next who spend large sums of money in ornaments and dress to plcase their ad- mirers, while they neglect their persons at home. Necklaces were much worn by Ro- man women, and eineralds were a favourite

stone for setting them off. Pearl carrings also were fashionable. Pliny describes the ‘ elenchus ' as a long kind of pearl, ‘ fasti- gata longitiuline,’ tapering to a point. He adds, “hos digitis suspendere et binos ac ternos auribus faeminarum gloria est.'’ (H. N. ix. 35.) Seneca, among other extrava- gances of luxury, says, “ video uniones non singulos singulis auribus comparatos (jam enim exercitatae aures oneri ferendo sunt) z junguntur inter se et insuper alii binis su· perponuntur. Non satis muliebris insania viros subjecerat nisi bina ac terna patri- monia auribus singulis pependissent.'' (De Benefic. vii. 9.)
